text:
tanító érintés • a #metoo mozgalom erősödésével újra előtérbe került az érintés-javítás-igazítás témaköre. 
te szereted, ha megérintenek jógaórán?

én bevallom, sokat javítok érintéssel. gyakran kerülök akár intim helyzetbe is a tanítványaimmal, mert úgy érzem, az adott helyzetben ez szükséges, vagy legalábbis hatékonyabb. viszont csak olyanokat érintek meg, akiket ismerek, akikkel megvan a kölcsönös bizalom. tudom magamról, hogy a szándékaim tiszták és kizárólag szakmaiak, de azt is tudnom kell, hogy a tanítvány is biztos ebben.

ha nincs meg ez a bizalmi viszony, akkor inkább elmagyarázom, min kellene változtatni. ez persze megakasztja a gyakorlás flow-ját, viszont azt gondolom, hogy inkább legyen ez a gyakorlás kicsit workshop-szerű, ha az otthoni gyakorlás minősége javul ettől. 
ha nem szeretnéd, hogy megérintsenek, nyugodtan jelezd az oktatónak. én például finoman szoktam szólni, hogy nem szeretném, ha belenyomnának a pózokba. pontosan tudom, meddig akarom beleengedni magam egy ászanába, csak akkor kérek fizikai segítséget, ha egyedül nem tudom kivitelezni a pózt. talán van egy-két csavarás, ahol néha jólesik egy finom rásegítés, de nem hiszek benne, hogy segíti a fejlődést, ha beletolják a gyakorlókat az előrehajlásokba.

a téma természetesen komplex, sokan sokféleképpen gondolkodnak róla, de annak a jelenségnek nem nagyon örülök, hogy egyre több oktató soha nem érinti meg a gyakorlókat, nehogy kellemetlen helyzetbe kerüljön. a jóga elsajátításához szükség van egy olyan vezetőre, akiben megbízol. ez a bizalmi viszony rengeteg korlátot felold, amit egyedül sokkal nehezebb leküzdeni. 
én nem is mennék olyan oktatóhoz gyakorolni, akinek félek az érintésétől. :) #teislehetszjógaoktató #jóga #gerincjóga #mandalajoga #metoo
name: Németh Gergő

text:
how many times has someone called you ‘angry’ when discussing feminism, intersectionality and feminist issues? how often have you felt thrown off guard and left wondering how to respond without ‘proving’ that person’s point? what do you feel in those situations and how do you react?
.
all too often commenting on someone’s ‘angry’ disposition can be a way to defer feelings of responsibility towards one’s own discomfort. it's a sure-fire way to character assassinate instead of engaging with the issues at hand in a serious way, even when to do so means to sit with uncomfortable feelings. it can often be used as a means to shut down conversation instead of opening up a dialogue.
.
what if that person is angry? when anger comes from a place of personal trauma and real life experience, a result of overlapping and constantly shifting privileges, is it ever okay to delegitimise anger when having these difficult conversations?
.
anger is a raw emotion which of course needs to be processed and confronted. but when that anger is denied and not heard by another person, the other’s own privileges and refusal to listen can silence and delegitimise another’s experience of injustice. .
is it time that we re-evaluated the value of anger? .
we would love to hear your thoughts and experiences.
.

text_retweet:
#repost (thanks for the tag!) @rapesurvivorsupport
・・・
i call those affected by sexual violence "survivors." i have spent the better part of a year waiting to feel some magical transition from "victim" to "survivor," as if one day i would conquer the key to stopping all of the immeasureable pain havoc wreaked on my life. truthfully, i have yet to feel like a survivor. on most days, i feel robbed and like i am grieving for a version of myself that i am not sure exists anymore. but more importantly, every victim/survivor deserved the right to claim whatever term makes then feel the most comfortable or more accurately represents their feelings.

secondly, we must use our language intentionally. something bad did not happen to me. someone did something bad to me. that someone raped me. it was not an accident, it was not "something bad, it was rape.
it is up to us to frame our trauma because unfortunately the rest of the world will not do it for us, or will do so with victim blaming and stigma. 
#ibelievethem .
.

text: || ich musste heute meine mama ins krankenhaus fahren, weil ich dachte sie bekommt gleich nen herzinfarkt bzw. schlaganfall (sie hatte vor paar tagen erhöhten blutdruck! und plötzlich wurde ihr heute schwindlich bzw war ihr gesicht rot angelaufen, atmen fiel ihr schwer.) also fuhr ich mit ihr dummerweise ins krankenhaus (notarzt lies sie mich nicht rufen, weil - meine mama ist wie sie ist.) das erste, was wir zu hören bekamen: „dann lernen sie deutsch! „ (weil ich mit mama mit ins besprechungszimmer mitgegangen bin- nur um sicherzugehen, dass mama alles versteht (und auch zu meiner beruhigung🙈)). die ärztin schickte uns wieder heim mit der begründung, es sei alles okay, mama bräuchte nur ruhe. oder ne kur. seelisch hat mir die dame nen herzinfarkt verpasst. || #rassismus #gegenrassismus

text:
[2.3] in joyce carol oates’s pulitzer finalist novel blonde, we are told how when marilyn, then a still very young norma jeane, was placed in a hot bath by her mother, gladys mortensen: she wanted to guard her little girl against the evils of the world. the water was so hot it nearly scorched young norma to death, an incident that led to gladys being hospitalized in a mental institution. this episode, so fateful in shaping norma’s relationship with her mother, likewise marked the beginning of marilyn’s special connection to water.

at the pinnacle of marilyn’s career, when her star shone the brightest, water became a gateway to the life of the stars. everyone remembers her friendship with frank sinatra and the dashing parties on the christina o (a favorite rendezvous for jet-setters such as greta garbo, john wayne, aristotle onassis, prince ranieri of monaco and princess grace).

text:
honestly, i would’ve never thought i’d ever be a victim of domestic violence until that day came. never in a million years does anyone think they will be in a domestic violence relationship... until it happens. the only way it’s preventable is through awareness, support, and speaking up. did i deserve to be abused? absolutely not. did i get abused because of my shape, size, hair, skin color... the answer is no. it can happen to anyone. i appreciate all of you who are following this post right now, and i just hope this page teaches you something 💜💜💜
#domesticviolence #domesticviolenceawareness #abuse #victim #survivor #ptsd #awareness #speakup #breakthesilence #spreadlove #shareyourstory #metoo #unbreakable

text_retweet:
@amanda.x.coleman
・・・
when did i become
one to hold back like this?
(i suppose it was that time he broke me)
i've regrown limbs since then
i've been so many people 
since then
but every once in a while
when the words get choked
between my throat and my tongue
the weaknesses i have left
will make themselves known
i feel small again
i crawl inside again
and you don't know well enough
to pull me back out .
.
.

text: as an amherst resident, i stand in solidarity with umass students and workers against right-wing terror and white supremacy on campus and globally. the melville undergrad dormitory had a racist death threat against black students written on the wall. the administration attempted to sweep it under the rug. a week later, a white supremacist drew a conservative flag on the walls of melville. again the administration is denying and trying to cover up the incident. the police were called on a staff member of color at the whitemore building. white supremacist identity europa recruitment flyers are being hung up all over campus. fascist and neofascist groups plan to double their recruitment efforts of college campuses this year. the umass police department continues to harass students of color. again,  the administration is dismissive and does nothing. this school/institution will not hold racists accountable because the institution itself perpetuates racism. students, workers, and surrounding amherst residents will not stand for this and we will continue to organize, mobilize, and demonstrate until justice is served. remember #richardcollins iii who was stabbed to death on the university of maryland campus by a white supremacist. join efforts and organizations on your campus! united we will not be defeated! democrat, republican, and ruling class ideological fear tactics of divide and conquer- "good" vs "bad" immigrant, "welfare queens," "real women"- white supremacy, xenophobia, nationalism, transphobia, fatphobia, ableism, neurotypicalism, classism, elitism- in solidarity we are waking up, un-indoctrinating ourselves, centering the voices, ideas, strategies, stories, and struggles of the most marginalized, and together we will win. #whitesupremacy #solidarity #unitedwewillnotbedefeated #blacklivesmatter #translivesmatter #immigrantsmakeamericagreat #metoo #fascism #internationalsocialistorganization #anarchy #bolsheviks #russianrevolution #democrat #republican

text: 🔮 @jsmithmma on @themajichour this conversation with one of our closest friends, jimmy smith, will really expose just how human we all are. as a former professional fighter, a bjj black belt, and the current host of the ufc, jimmy may appear to be a “tough guy” from the outside, but here, among friends, he displays the findings of his life-long self reflective practice. he shares his experiences as a child growing up with an alcoholic, detached father. we explore how jimmy’s charismatic personality was born, and why there’ll likely never be a #metoo story involving him. from the legendary adventure of him doing shrooms with his mom in amsterdam, to the turbulent tale of him having to act as our impromptu bodyguard during our years on the road together with bellatormma, this episode is packed with intriguing tid-bits, wether you’re an mma fan or not. click link in our bio to listen!!

text: i want all survivors to know: you matter. i believe you. we believe you. you are stronger than you know. it was not your fault. there will always be an army behind you. we will  never stop fighting for you. you deserve to be taken seriously. demand justice. don’t live in fear and silence. i love you all so much. i’m still shaking from how moving our protest was. i hope everyone there felt as empowered as i did. it was so beautiful to see people drive by and be touched by us. it was so amazing to see some boys hide their faces in what i assume is shame. hopefully we help end some silence. hopefully we were able to show people that this is a real, everyday issue. hopefully some people maybe realized they are part of the problem and will start pushing to be better. end rape culture! im so proud of everyone who came out with us today!

text:
don’t let anyone 👏 dull your 👏 shine. today a man stared and grimaced at my tights while walking very close to me (a loved one bought them for me from a name brand popular in europe and i think they are fun and interesting). i stared back. he eventually walked away. it’s sad how quickly people judge on the smallest of details, how some strange people sexualize others. it’s scary and not ok. protect yourself and protect your heart. you are never asking for it. ❌
i felt better though talking with my coworkers after. we laughed over some comments i made. so talk about it. and don’t feel badly about not looking or talking to strangers. ❕honestly, it’s a hard time for a lot of women. you come first and don’t owe any ill-intentioned person on the street anything. 🥇
#overit #doyou #bodypositivity #metoo #protectyourheart #protectyoheart #feminist #feminism

text:
я привыкла делиться своими мыслями, но какой в том толк, если я не доношу до людей полезную информацию.
на мой взгляд, очень важно высказывать свое мнение относительно того или иного вопроса, коих в современном мире преогромное количество. 
так вот среди этого множества есть, например, проблема социальных сетей. 
очевидно, вы не раз сталкивались с грубостью в интернете, и считается, что это все природа отдельного человека, его характер. но задумывались ли вы, что проблема - в окружающем нас мире (который мы сами сформировали, кстати)?
то, с чем мы сталкиваемся ежедневно, неизбежно влияет на наше сознание; а сталкиваемся мы с агрессией и негативом в целом.
в интернете легче написать грубость, легче ответить человеку грубостью. тем для дискуссий полно (сейчас это чаще политические споры), так что причин посоревноваться в том, кто "ударит" больнее предостаточно. безусловно, есть так называемые "адекватные" люди, которые умеют правильно реагировать на чужое мнение, каким бы оно ни было.
и все же нельзя отрицать, что человек еще не научился справляться с агрессией, потому что в настоящее время понятие "сплоченность" заслуживает эпитета vague (fr. расплывчатый)
___
"чтобы пресечь агрессию, нужно сплотиться"
___
все существующие движения, будь то американское #ivoted или недавнее #metoo против харассмента, действительно работают, потому что люди поддерживают идею, распространяют ее, потому что они делают это вместе и с определнной целью.
* вдохновлено статьей агустина фуэнтеса "антисоциальные сети", @natgeo.russia , август 2018.
.
это был первый пост из серии #foodforthought .
.
.
#opinion #inspired  #antisocialmedia #internet #people #solidarity

text:
jupiter in #scorpio♏ collectively
one year ago jupiter, planet of abundance, growth, and magnification, entered♏. spending 13 months in the fixed, water🌊 sign that refuses to look away from the horrors, betrayals, #trauma and #pain that are the result of all abuses of power, #jupiter began to make obvious what we as a society have denied for too long.5 days after jupiter entered ♏ and in response to the allegations that began to unravel the decades of #sexualharassment, abuse, and cover-ups of one of the most powerful men in hollywood, alyssa milano re-tweeted a statement that was over a decade old from the founder of the ‘me too’ movement, tarana burke. she wrote, “if you’ve been sexually harassed or assaulted write ‘me too’ as a reply to this tweet.” milano wanted to “give people a sense of the magnitude of the problem.” jupiter in ♏ obliged. the civil rights activist and founder of the #metoo movement, tarana burke, has since become one of the most important figure heads of the long-standing, #multi-generational, movement to understand and address the #impact of #sexualviolence for those that have survived it. jupiter spends approximately 1year in each sign, returning back to that sign every 12 years. burke founded the ’me too’ movement in 2006. 12 years ago. our #movements have a movement and a timing all their own.
for the first few weeks and months of jupiter’s travels through♏, our feeds were plastered with admissions of how frequently these #abuses occurs.absorbing these admissions en masse, we have been asked to collectively hold the broken, shattered parts of self and #society that this moment was, and still is, bringing up for us to bear witness to.this fall, at the end of the planet of plenty’s journey through this emotionally #intense sign, #venus began its retrograde within the same deep waters. concurrently, dr. christine blasey ford’s brave testimony in front of the senate echoed that of anita hill’s so many years before.dr. ford’s testimony struck the same chord that the ‘me too’ movement had the year previous. as venus retrograded over the degrees in which jupiter was 1year prior the howling in our hearts was once more #shared publicly.👇👇👇

"третья волна феминизма - тоска": памела против #metoo.
⠀
памела андерсон высказала свою позицию о третьей волне феминизма в австралийской программе "60 минут".
⠀
звезда фильма "спасатели малибу" откровенно заявила, что не разделяет взгляды движения #мetoo, которое возникло на фоне скандала о домогательствах кинопродюсера харви вайнштейна.
⠀
"я - феминистка, но я думаю, что третья волна феминизма — это тоска».
⠀
вспоминая ситуацию с голивудским кинопродюсером, андерсон недвусмысленно дала понять, что жертвы домогательств сами виновны в случившемся.
⠀
«мама учила меня не ходить по отелям с незнакомцами. если кто-то открывает дверь в банном халате и предполагается, что у вас деловая встреча, может быть,  нужно пойти к кому-то другому».
⠀
а что вы думаете о феминизме в его современном виде?

text:
ep. 160-here’s my #interview with one of the contributors in my consent book, the consent guidebook, sexual health educator nicole holmes. we chat about the difference between #yesmeansyes and #nomeansno #enthusiasticconsent #safewords and more.

about consent guidebook contributor nicole holmes: nicole is a sexual health educator with a focus on hiv/sti prevention among youth and black women in addition to #lgbtq sexual health education. she contributes commentary to sexual health news using the facebook page @nickyheartspubhealth in addition to the hashtag #safesexsaturday ...nicole has taught #sexualhealtheducation to students in juvenile detention centers in addition to sexual health education in #rehab facilities as well. nicole believes in utilizing a health model of de-stigmatizing sexuality and making #sexualhealth accessible for all. check out more about #theconsentguidebook and it’s contributors at www.theconsentguidebook.com. listen on  itunes, stitcher, or podomatic (pc-friendly) #podcast #metoo #timesup #consenteducation

text:
here’s how to handle ‘the houseguest who just won’t leave.’ depression isn’t just an incredibly devastating mental illness, it’s also one of the most common. approximately 16.2 million american adults have experienced a major depressive episode in their lives, as well as 3.1 million adolescents ages 12 to 17, according to 2016 statistics from the national institute of mental health. if you’re one of the millions affected, it’s difficult to know how to deal with depression when you’re in the thick of it writes ana valens.
you may not even be aware that you have depression until your symptoms have spiked. but people with depression can learn how to cope, and one step at a time, you can get your life back on track. https://youwillbearwitness.com/2018/11/06/what-can-you-do-to-cope-with-depression/ #youwillbearwitness #erinfado #ptsdawareness #ptsd #doitfordolly #peterfox #ptsdsurvivor #ptsdrecovery #stopracism #stopbullying #stopchildabuse #metoo #trauma #therapydog

text:
in 2006, civil rights activist tarana burke, now 45, founded what would become the #metoo movement to support survivors of sexual violence, particularly young women of color from low-wealth communities. “some stuff that’s happened has been heavy-handed. but that’s not the fault of the movement,” burke said. “we’ve never taken a step back to listen, to really understand the effects of sexual violence, from sexual harassment to rape and murder. and so you’re dealing with millions of women, mostly, who have been shamed into silence forever now having their own personal reckonings.” read more from our interview with the activist via the link in our bio.
(📷: kk ottesen)

text:
with the #metoo campaign currently going around, i feel like i need to share something. if you are a survivor of childhood sexual abuse, there is something you can do to help you on your journey to heal. 
the younique foundation offers a free retreat to survivors of childhood sexual abuse. they don't force younique products on you, they don't even use our products in the makeover and photoshoot because they don't want there to be even an ounce of room for someone to say they have the wrong intentions. this foundation has one purpose, and one purpose only: to help you heal. 
no business. no sales. nothing except opportunities for you to rediscover your self-worth and heal. you are powerful beyond measure. 
if you want to know more, please check out www.youniquefoundation.org, where you can read more and apply to attend the retreat or contact me. 
#nomore1in4 #reclaimhope  #ibelieveyou

text:
⚓️❤️ many people have asked me why i got this particular tattoo. so i’m here to tell you the meaning behind each item. 
2017 was one of the worst years of my life. in a total of 6 times i tried to commit suicide and in 2018 about 3. as many of you may know i am drawn to anchors. anchors give me the sense of comfort and hope. 
the particular verse i carry with me while dealing with hard times is; hebrews 6:19 which reads, “we have this hope as a anchor for the soul, firm and secure.” the compass and wheel go together. although i have been lost and it was hard to get through such a hard time and doing so by myself because i was scared to let others in, i know god is steering me in the right direction and i know that with him anything is possible. anything. (the flowers are because i like flowers there’s no real reason for these 😂) i am so blessed to be alive, and i truly couldn’t thank my closest friends and family enough for being there for me in all the ways they don’t even understand yet. 
#metoo 💔

allyson really was awesome, and i thank you so much for the amazing job you did. 🙂

text:
my amazing sister posted this last night, and i wanted to share because it’s true. and not only for voting. 🇺🇸
. if you post about a cause you believe in, you’re twice as likely to actually donate or volunteer for that cause. 🤳🏼
. 14% of facebook users have changed their mind about a social or political issue because of social media articles and posts. 💻

if you don’t believe this, think about hashtags and trends. why did food photos, throwback thursday’s, and #metoo ever become a thing? it was because people were “seeking attention,” they were “basic,” they were “flexing.” i know it can get annoying to see the same posts over and over again. but please don’t hate on something that can actually make a difference for our country. hate on the food pics or throwbacks which don’t actually matter. or better yet, don’t hate!

this graphic is from my super amazing sister @michelleegus. her account is private so sometimes i have to share the best stuff. 💗

text:
i still remember the days when i was praying for what i have now. ⁣
⁣
this time last year, we were entering the third trimester and i cannot tell you what a relief it was to get this far in our pregnancy. you see, both of my girls are rainbow babies. rainbow babies are babies who is born after a miscarriage, stillbirth or loss of an infant. ⁣
⁣
i’ve been pregnant four times in my life. but, two of the babies i made, didn’t quite make it to this side of heaven. i’ll never fully understand why things like this have to happen in our world, but one of the silver linings that loss produces is this: insane gratefulness for the things we do have. ⁣
⁣
if you’re in the middle of a storm and you aren’t sure you’ll make it out... hold on. it won’t be long, now, darling. i promise. the best is yet to come. you just can’t see it yet. 🙏🏼✨ #madeforbrave

text:
for many of us who have overcome trauma or abuse, it can be incredibly painful or triggering to see childhood photos. .
.
i look at this and can remember when i first started inner child therapy, i hated seeing these photos. i had grown to believe the “inner child” was responsible for my anger, rage, and the unbalanced heart and mind that made my decisions. .
.
while i can still see his sadness and uncertainty because that is what those times were made of, i see his resolve in knowing that i’ve got it from here. his heavy decision making days are over. he gets to rest because i’m taking care of him. he knows the older version of himself is willing to fight for his safety in a moments notice. .
.
i wish there was a simple and easy way to convince each of you who are on an overcoming journey: “please be so incredibly kind to each part of you.  especially the parts you feel are hurting.” .
.
“they...need...love...the...most.”
.
.
be well! i’m fighting for each of you....
.
.

text:
women in da house! 🤟🏽🤟🏽🤟🏽 the us woke up to itself today. finally, what looks like (slightly more) representative democracy has been achieved. 
news broke overnight that the us election has swept a record number of women into congress, fired up by disgust with donald trump, emboldened by the #metoo movement and making the democratic party more diverse and younger than ever.

the class of 2019 includes the youngest congressional women in history, 29-year-olds alexandria ocasio-cortez from new york and abby finkenauer from iowa, as well as the first two native american women, and the first two muslim women, palestinian-american rashida tlaib and somali-american ilhan omar.
with results still trickling in, at least 120 women will serve in congress, a record 98 in the house of representatives and 22 in the senate, says the center for american women and politics at rutgers university.

the previous house record was 85. the wins bump up female representation in the lower house to at least 23 percent, still dismal in the world rankings. but an uptick nonetheless. “voters were more determined than ever to defend women's rights at the ballot box and in the halls of congress,” toni van pelt, president of the national organization for women, said in a statement. “women voted for health care, for reproductive rights, for economic justice, and for gender equality.” .
#congress #congress2018 #election2018 #womeninthehouse #girledworld ✖️✖️

text:
women in da house! 🤟🏽🤟🏽🤟🏽 the us woke up to itself today. 🇱🇷 finally, what looks like (slightly more) representative democracy has been achieved. 
news broke overnight that the us election has swept a record number of women into congress, fired up by disgust with donald trump, emboldened by the #metoo movement and making the democratic party more diverse and younger than ever.

the class of 2019 includes the youngest congressional women in history, 29-year-olds alexandria ocasio-cortez from new york and abby finkenauer from iowa, as well as the first two native american women, and the first two muslim women, palestinian-american rashida tlaib and somali-american ilhan omar.
with results still trickling in, at least 120 women will serve in congress, a record 98 in the house of representatives and 22 in the senate, says the center for american women and politics at rutgers university.

the previous house record was 85. the wins bump up female representation in the lower house to at least 23 percent, still dismal in the world rankings. but an uptick nonetheless. “voters were more determined than ever to defend women's rights at the ballot box and in the halls of congress,” toni van pelt, president of the national organization for women, said in a statement. “women voted for health care, for reproductive rights, for economic justice, and for gender equality.” .
#congress #congress2018 #election2018 #womeninthehouse #girledworld ✖️✖️
@girledworld

text:
ilustración y palabras de la genia de @lola.vendetta 💚💪🏼 #sororidadenlarae
・・・
no voy a decirte que eres una exagerada, que te lo estás inventando, porqué quién soy yo para juzgar a nadie. quien soy yo para creerme poseedora de una única verdad, cuando verdades hay tantas como individuos. es tan cierto que algunxs aprendieron a "querer" haciendo daño, como que otrxs entendieron que para ser queridxs tocaba sufrir. ¿qué nos cuesta escuchar sin juzgar? nada, escuchar no nos cuesta nada. se trata hasta de apagar el cerebro, y oír con todo lo demás. escuchar no nos cuesta ni tan siquiera amor, porque sabemos que este cuando más se expande más se multiplica. juzgar requiere trabajo. no perdáis el tiempo juzgando a nadie, no invirtáis vuestra vida en hacer otra cosa que no sea dejar que el amor - el de verdad, el que no entiende de "yo más y tú menos" - salga de las cenizas como la flor que nace en el asfalto. escuchad. "cuando hay suficiente amor, nada es demasiado complicado y siempre hay tiempo". #metoo #yotambién

- after a year and a half of preparation for my first beauty pageant; the miss earth pageant, i was excited to travel back to the philippines for the 6th time. the hospitality of the filipinos is not found anywhere else. the philippines is like a second home to me. i joined the pageant to make a difference and be a role model to those around me. i enjoyed a majority of the pageant, but what i did not know, is that a specific sponsor from the manila yacht club would change the way i see pageantry and sponsors. the sponsor who’s name is amado s. cruz became a problem for many of the delegates, including myself. to focus on only myself, i was pulled aside multiple times to be invited to boracay, private islands and into his house and insisted that i and “the latino women dance for him.” amado s. cruz grabbed my bare backside at the national costume competition where i was able to push him away, but he consistently told me not to tell anyone about any of the instances. at the manila yacht club, amado s. cruz ensured that the team managers and security personnel were separated in another room, this is where he made many girls uncomfortable. a groups of us left the room because we felt uncomfortable, but amado s. cruz followed us and insisted that we stayed inside to dance with him. we asked our team managers to bring us to the busses, which took over 20 minutes for them finally to do. later on that night @missjamieyvonne and @miss.earth.england spoke on the phone with lorraine schuck, the vice president of miss earth, who assured them that amado s. cruz would not be at any other event. from the moment the pageant started until coronation night, amado s. cruz was at every event and dinner he could physically get to. since other delegates have posted, multiple other queens from past years have come out about the same behavior. i want to help put a stop to this sponsor being apart of the miss earth international pageant because he has become a problem for years. 
#missearth2018 #missearth #metoo @missearth
name: JB Tara

text:
today's workout got me feelin all types of ways. all the feelings. rage. sadness. joy. bliss. pride. it was my first workout in over a week because leaving my house, moving from my bed, talking to anyone or being seen outside of work was just not going to happen if i could help it. this type of episode is completely out of my control. 
validating let alone, acknowledging my feelings has never been easy for me. i use positivity to ignore them or just lash out. in the last year, i learned it was because of an illness. which made the rest of my life make so much more sense. 
now- learning how to accept and deal with them is my latest learning experience in this odd hand of cards i've been dealt. 
sometimes, you need a break to sort through and remind yourself know you're okay. you're still the queen because this is the shit you survive. 
i enjoy the stories i read. reminds me, i'm not alone. so i hope this is helpful to at least one of you. 
#emotional #bipolar2 #manic #depression #hyper #validated #mentalillness #awarness #pride #joy #bliss #rage #queen #survive #advocate #rest #restart #medication #therapy #metoo

text:
(not originally mine. apologies that i can't recall where i saw it first.) my n abandoned her son to babysitters, her enabler mother, and me many times, without a care in the world for her son. she cared more about her son as a photography subject for her portfolio, and people's perception of her as a doting parent.  in reality, she resented the attention and care that our son got as well as the time and resource requirements. she told me a few times that i loved our son more than her, like it's a competition. and in the end, in addition to discarding me, she also discarded her son. he hasn't received a card, let alone a present, for his birthday or christmas, over the last two years. yet she continues to use him as a prop claiming how much she weepily misses him, to gain narcicisstic fuel.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

cnn

text:
thank you to @allie._.gator02 for trusting me to share your story. please read below at your discretion as this deals with #sexualassault. *editor’s note* - i don’t think she has much of a support system surrounding her so if you believe her, please consider leaving a comment below to let her know she has your love and support. i think it would mean a lot for her to know she’s not alone 🖤
i also want to add for anyone reading this, even if you say yes a million times, you’re still allowed to change your mind and it’s not your fault if you do that. ................................. “over the summer three boys video taped me. one of them was my ex, we were gonna hook up...but then i got scared and i pushed him off. he kept pushing for me to let him, and i gave in because he wouldn't stop. i hated it. he made me close my eyes and that's when he recorded me. i didn't know until later that summer when i was at my aunts. they put me in a group chat and called me a whore and a worthless slut. they told me it would be best if i slit my wrists and died. i tried telling my parents. my dad was worried but my mom just said if i didn't want to be called a slut then to keep my knees shut. when school started he kept making fun of me. i shaved my head. i tried to let go and he made fun of me for it. i tried going to the school, but they wouldn't do anything since it wasn't on school grounds. my dad won't let me go to the cops because it would be too much. he said they wouldn't do anything because it's been months. i don't know what to do. i'm just a joke to them.”

text:
well the midterms happened....and we took the house y'all!!! some people are disappointed because we narrowly lost out on seats we never thought we should be able to win, i'm looking at you arizona, florida and texas. we get it, it wasn’t the blue wave or the revolution we wanted… but really, dems managed to flip seats that have been in the gop's pocket for decades and more women were elected than ever before! not to mention the first muslim women in congress, first openly gay governor, first native american in congress and the youngest people to ever serve congress.

so what does all this mean? voting matters. youth vote matters. progress matters. women matter. 
well done america - well most of it. alabama and west virginia we aren't proud of you. you just couldn't leave reproductive rights alone could you.

text: 10 years ago when the image on the left was captured, i was just a normal high school girl trying out a cucumber cleansing diet because i wanted to be skinny — a body image problem i still am struggling with in the form of severe eating disorders. i had no idea why people laughed at me when i used it as my social media profile picture. i understand the loaded meaning of this picture now, and find it almost impossible to desexualize my 16-year-old self from this visual culture — i keep explaining and will keep on explaining, though. why do we think this way? #pillarofsalt #genderstereotypes #metoo #femininity #masculinity #thegoodmanproject @halcyon_inspires

text:
•
five years ago tonight i was in the darkest space of my life. 
full of pain, doubt and fear. 
certain i was worthy of nothing better. 
shame spilling out of every part of me. 
and still i made a decision that it would be the very last night i would numb it all with alcohol.•
•
tomorrow i will celebrate 5 years of sobriety. but tonight i will celebrate (with a workout) the girl who on nothing more than a a glimpse of hope, poured the rest of the bottle down the drain & never picked another drink up. •
•
cheers to hope, blind bravery, and showing up through it all. whenever i think i can’t do something, or that this next thing is too hard- i remember november 7, 2013 and i know i can do this too. ❤️

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text: vogliamo parlare di quanto sia bella asia argento? ma bellezza a parte, volevo esprimere il mio stupore e disappunto per il fatto che nessuno mi abbia mai spinto a conoscerla, a vedere cosa fa, cosa dice. mi sono informata un pochino di più in seguito alle ultime notizie sulla sua relazione con fabrizio corona. ho letto le sue parole, le ho trovate commoventi. allora l’ho cercata su youtube, ho trovato l’album “total entrophy” e lo sto adorando. lo trovo schietto, disordinato e armonioso. come la vita. poi l’ho sentita parlare in un video e ho pensato che parla col cuore in mano. allora l’ho cercata su instagram e la prima cosa che ho visto è che aveva postato nelle sue storie una frase di alda merini “la miglior vendetta è la felicità”. posso dirvi che idea mi sono fatta? mi sembra una persona trasparente. che ha il coraggio di mettere la faccia per le cose in cui crede e che non ha paura di sporcarsi le mani. ha i suoi problemi e le sue turbolenze (come tutti), e i suoi scheletri non sono nell’armadio, ma sul balcone, in bella vista. perché non dovrebbe continuare ad essere il volto di #metoo? cito de andre’ “c’è ben poco merito nella virtù, c’è ben poca colpa nell’errore” #asiaargento #scoperta

text: i made this for a club at school which will create a zine about women’s issues. this is supposed to represent the victims of sexual harassment. the #metoo is drawn on her cheeks like warpaint because of the war she is fighting emotionally, and she doesn’t have a mouth because some sexual assault victims can’t speak up about their experiences. this is something i care about, and i’m glad that i can create art about it.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

text:
beauty in ashes
.

2 samuel 13:19–22 (esv): and tamar put ashes on her head and tore the long robe that she wore. and she laid her hand on her head and went away, crying aloud as she went. 
and her brother absalom said to her, “has amnon your brother been with you? now hold your peace, my sister. he is your brother; do not take this to heart.” so tamar lived, a desolate woman, in her brother absalom’s house. when king david heard of all these things, he was very angry. but absalom spoke to amnon neither good nor bad, for absalom hated amnon, because he had violated his sister tamar. .
could tamar find beauty? strength? joy?  healing? justice? .
she was told to just get over it! 
#metoo for tamar .. women have been defiled for too many years! .
how do women find healing? how can they rise from the ashes and be seen as pure ... beautiful ... strong ... overcomers?

my side of the miss earth international experience:
- after a year and a half of preparation for my first beauty pageant; the miss earth pageant, i was excited to travel back to the philippines for the 6th time. the hospitality of the filipinos is not found anywhere else. the philippines is like a second home to me. i joined the pageant to make a difference and be a role model to those around me. i enjoyed a majority of the pageant, but what i did not know, is that a specific sponsor from the manila yacht club would change the way i see pageantry and sponsors. the sponsor who’s name is amado s. cruz became a problem for many of the delegates, including myself. to focus on only myself, i was pulled aside multiple times to be invited to boracay, private islands and into his house and insisted that i and “the latino women dance for him.” amado s. cruz grabbed my bare backside at the national costume competition where i was able to push him away, but he consistently told me not to tell anyone about any of the instances. at the manila yacht club, amado s. cruz ensured that the team managers and security personnel were separated in another room, this is where he made many girls uncomfortable. a groups of us left the room because we felt uncomfortable, but amado s. cruz followed us and insisted that we stayed inside to dance with him. we asked our team managers to bring us to the busses, which took over 20 minutes for them finally to do. later on that night @missjaimeyvonne and @miss.earth.england spoke on the phone with lorraine schuck, the vice president of miss earth, who assured them that amado s. cruz would not be at any other event. from the moment the pageant started until coronation night, amado s. cruz was at every event and dinner he could physically get to. since other delegates have posted, multiple other queens from past years have come out about the same behavior. i want to help put a stop to this sponsor being apart of the miss earth international pageant because he has become a problem for years. 
#missearth2018 #missearth #metoo @missearth
name: miss earth lover

text:
#letherspeak this is an important one. gagging survivors of sexual assault from speaking out is hugely problematic and sends the message that they have no agency, no control over their own stories and their own lives, just as they had no choice in what was done to them. it protects predators and silences survivors. yet section 194k of the crimes act does precisely that. the laws in tasmania and nt, which state that sexual assault survivors cannot speak out and cannot appear in media or be named even with the survivor’s full consent, must come into line with other states, to reflect a survivor’s right to tell her or his own story if they choose. please consider signing the petition here: https://www.megaphone.org.au/petitions/let-her-speak

to understand how shockingly unjust this law is, read about *jane doe, and why she wants to speak out, here: https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/let-her-speak-shocking-reason-woman-cant-tell-her-sexual-assault-story/news-story/718ad770a25833970f961c551f3eaab1 (i hate having to call her jane doe. it’s not her name and she doesn’t want to be known as jane doe. the law prevents me from giving her the dignity of her own identity.) this is just one horrific story among many.
#letherspeak #speakout #respectsurvivors #speakingout #metoo #survivorsmatter 
see also: 'let sexual assault victims speak: tara moss calls for change to tasmanian law' (link in the bio) please consider supporting this campaign, which has been designed by nina funnell in partnership with end rape on campus and marque lawyers, and is supported by *jane doe and many other survivors, including myself. join us in pushing for urgent law reform now: www.megaphone.org.au/petitions/let-her-speak

- after a year and a half of preparation for my first beauty pageant; the miss earth pageant, i was excited to travel back to the philippines for the 6th time. the hospitality of the filipinos is not found anywhere else. the philippines is like a second home to me. i joined the pageant to make a difference and be a role model to those around me. i enjoyed a majority of the pageant, but what i did not know, is that a specific sponsor from the manila yacht club would change the way i see pageantry and sponsors. the sponsor who’s name is amado s. cruz became a problem for many of the delegates, including myself. to focus on only myself, i was pulled aside multiple times to be invited to boracay, private islands and into his house and insisted that i and “the latino women dance for him.” amado s. cruz grabbed my bare backside at the national costume competition where i was able to push him away, but he consistently told me not to tell anyone about any of the instances. at the manila yacht club, amado s. cruz ensured that the team managers and security personnel were separated in another room, this is where he made many girls uncomfortable. a groups of us left the room because we felt uncomfortable, but amado s. cruz followed us and insisted that we stayed inside to dance with him. we asked our team managers to bring us to the busses, which took over 20 minutes for them finally to do. later on that night @missjaimeyvonne and @miss.earth.england spoke on the phone with lorraine schuck, the vice president of miss earth, who assured them that amado s. cruz would not be at any other event. from the moment the pageant started until coronation night, amado s. cruz was at every event and dinner he could physically get to. since other delegates have posted, multiple other queens from past years have come out about the same behavior. i want to help put a stop to this sponsor being apart of the miss earth international pageant because he has become a problem for years. 
#missearth2018 #missearth #metoo @missearth

text:
i’m watching the sun go down today, and i’m thinking about betrayal.

today, not october 31st, is the actual day the sun is at the halfway point between fall equinox (mabon) and winter solstice (yule). this is solar samhain.

we also have witch’s remembrance day, a global holy day to remember the millions of people who have been murdered in the name of the god yahweh and abrahamic faiths over the last 5,000+ years.

coincidentally, we also have the new moon in scorpio happening at the same time. every month, the night leading up to the new moon in ancient greece was dedicated to hecate, and to worship her, practitioners would hold a dinner and discuss their magical acts for the month, bringing drinks and leftovers out to crossroads where three roads met. every year, the kali puja is held on the days and nights of the new moon in scorpio. her temples are filled with devotees laying sacrifices at the great goddesses feet, in hopes that she will protect the faithful, destroying their enemies and granting them peace from the karmic struggle.

behind every #metoo story, behind every person who is saying #timesup, underlying the print of every story documenting every abuse that is destroying our world, there is this chorus rising into one voice. it does not matter who is speaking, she is talking. it is medusa, screaming. it is lilith, betrayed and cast out. it is hina, seduced by her father, it is persephone, dragged to hades. it is saule, wailing for her daughter, violated. nemesis, leda, akycha. 
rape, betrayal, and abandonment are well documented in the religions of the past. anywhere the goddess reigned, and patriarchy moved in, the goddess was raped, crushed underfoot. romans would literally carve statues of the local goddesses being raped or on their knees in chains at the foot of a roman soldier. but it happened everywhere. from greenland to hawaii, from the ojibwe to the slavs, the destruction and subjugation of the goddess has been universal.

the rest of this piece, and a ritual for working with this energy, have just been posted at my site.
📸 thom lang
#whatwitchesdo #kali #morrigan #hecate #metoo #timesup #goodnightpatriarchy #neveragaintheburningtimes

text:
when you get triggered af // 4 steps to letting go of irritation 🔥
.

you know, so you can live a sober life beyond your wildest dreams.
and enjoy it.
.

this is how we do it…
.

remove your buttons
.

it is not about removing those who push your buttons.
because that’s impossible.
it’s better to get free.
.

to remove your buttons:
.

1.  meditate
.

meditation helps you become more aware of your internal world.
so yea if you want freedom and peace and joy.
and all the good things.
then…. meditate.
.

2.  own your buttons
.

realize that what triggers you is yours.
these are your buttons.
.

not the one who appears to be “doing something to you.”
.

if you’re hysterical.
it’s historical.
.

when we 100% own our experience we can transform it.
so take full responsibility for what irritates you.
.

3.  get curious af .

as the wise sage gi joe once said..
“knowing is half the battle.”
.

yep, become curious. .

inquire to find out why you’re irritated.
what is coming up to be healed.
pause and check.
.

this is a big clue to your  f r e e d o m.
.

4.  boundary up like a mofo
.

you’re not a victim.
and you’re also not a doormat.
.

you’ve meditated to gain clarity on what sets you off.
you’ve owned your internal world completely and totally.
you’ve inquired to see what’s been called forth to be healed.
then become an emotional sobriety ninja.
with a blackbelt in boundaries.
.

decide if you’re going to communicate them to someone.
or just know what they are yourself and adjust accordingly.
.

and then, of course, hold those boundaries in place.
praying can help with finding the strength to hold your boundaries.
.

and now a huge delicious high five.
this is the path of the spiritual warrior.
you’ve just learned how to use your irritation.
for your enlightenment.
.

for your evolution.
.

you may even be excited the next time you get triggered. 🙊
because you know how to handle it.
and that you’re in the process.
of getting free.
.

each trigger is a chance for more freedom.
.

let’s get free.
.

xx kir . ❤️

text:
trauma. what do we actually mean when we use this word and what determines whether an even is traumatizing or not?
.
in the first installment of our interdisciplinary series on understanding and healing trauma, i explore how we have come to define trauma as well as my own experiences growing up in the shadow of abuse.
.
sharing such intimacies with complete strangers is not easy but i genuinely hope, that through this series, everyone who takes the time to read it will learn something; whether its about themselves, a friend, a lover or a family member.
.
for me, its about knowing that i am no longer defined or limited by what happened to me, i am what i choose to become and i have within me what it takes to make that a reality💓
.
next in the series: trauma’s impact on the brain followed by one reiki practitioner’s approach to healing trauma.

text:
brace yourself, this one is going to be longer than usual. today was my #metoo moment. i know us wahine have had plenty before some more than others. social media struggles to talk about the tough stuff. so here it goes. if i could just save one woman that was in my shoes, i will be forever grateful. on january the 28th 2018, i got on a plane and left my abuser. it takes a women 7 attempts to get out of an abusive relationship. which i think is about right. it took a few too many hits to change my life forever. since then, i have been trying to convince myself that “it wasn’t that bad” when it really was.

its really amazing how us wahine become so resilient, so quick to adapt to change and yet so incredibly private about our relationships when they turn sour. i knew all the statistics, i have always been taught to never allow a man to place a finger on you. i am a smart woman, with a good career and amazing friends, with a decent upbringing. i never in my life thought that the women covered in bruises, trying to come up with stories to hide them would be me.  this is my chance to change my story, to cut the instagram bs about life being perfect all the time, and my way to empower those women who are going through similar things.  because 2018 has become a time of change we are educating ourselves to do better and frankly, i never want to raise my daughter or my son in a world where this is acceptable. new life starts here. #metoo #wecandobetter

text:
the animals were imperfect,
long-tailed,
unfortunate in their heads.
little by little they
put themselves together,
making themselves a landscape,
acquiring spots, grace, flight.
the cat,
only the cat
appeared complete and proud:
he was born completely finished,
walking alone and knowing what he wanted.

man wants to be fish or fowl,
the snake would like to have wings
the dog is a disoriented lion,
the engineer would like to be a poet,
the fly studies to be a swift,
the poet tries to imitate the fly,
but the cat
only wants to be a cat
and any cat is a cat
from his whiskers to his tail,
from his hopeful vision of a rat
to the real thing,
from the night to his golden eyes. https://youwillbearwitness.com/2018/11/06/ode-to-the-cat-2/ #youwillbearwitness #erinfado #emdr #ptsdawareness #ptsd #trauma #peterfox #ptsdsurvivor #ptsdrecovery #stopracism #stopbullying #stopchildabuse #metoo #doitfordolly #therapydog #cardinalpell

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

*
i stayed up super late last night. my body demanded a nap today and it got one. i have a lot on my mind - good and bad. i think that’s why balance is so important. you don’t need life toppling over in either direction. a steady and manageable balance is the key to handling it all.
*

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text: on an era of #metoo movement where women empowerment is such an inspiring force in our global community, we at @missearthexclusiveofficial value the effort of each and everyone that no woman must be harassed in all forms either physical, verbal or sexually abused, much more to be bullied. but in the end of the day, we must stand up for the #truth and set it free. pageantry nowadays is not just merely a beauty pageant as it evolved into an advocacy platform. thanks to @missearth, who is one of the pillars and the earliest major pageant to incorporate beauty with a cause. while the issue with @missjaimeyvonne of canada alongside claims of @sheedy.emmamae and others is quiet a brave act and empowering, but we must not blame team managers and tarnish the reputation of other delegates who only did was to represent and make their country proud.  we ask everyone not to bully miss earth delegates who defends and stand up for miss earth organization as well as those who stand up for miss canada. lets not add fire to the issue but let the two parties settle it in humane and professional way. the world is already polluted with plastics, much more with humans who care less for our environment.

text: today was literally one of the best days of my life. to be working with the distinguished documentarian tomas @auksas , making a film about #intersex , our history and place in art..to feel such huge ❤️ and respect for @rivergallo and be on this extraordinary @gaptoofentertainment ride with @sadecjoseph & @tildacanyouhearme . especially after getting so sick- mentally & physically from being on the wrong hormones , from 12-48..and now on #testosterone i’m finally feeling my powerful authentic self & facing my trauma on a deep level ; and seeing why it all made me so right to the edge suicidally #depressed.. hanging in there & staying sober, with lots of support.. knowing that my creative mentor #derekjarman has given me all the tools to pass on to this next generation of souls who have such important work to do raising consciousness for our human race, animals & mother earth.. receiving such kindness from people in #hollywood who are welcoming us and open to support & help us build new hollywood - post #metoo and to help us all have fun moving beyond the patriarchy.. not to matriarchy (we did that already) but instead to a place of connectedness & oneness that can be open to and honor diversity for the gifts.. ps i didn’t buy this house #yet (i’m a broke ass 1/2 bitch #justfortoday ) @disnapback.official perfect for our @auksas #intersexarmyoflove

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text: censorship is all around us, from social media to television to academia to government institutions. what is hidden and blocked from view reveals the cultural norms that override expression and - subsequently - artists' efforts to contest such norms. alison stinely's art was censored before finding a place at the linda matney art gallery. women artists, like stinely, have had their ideas blocked by institutions for centuries. how does her experience with censorship fit within the era of the #metoo movement? what does the silencing of female expression in today's culture mean for women? join alison stinely, diana blanchard gross, vittorio colaizzi, lita tirak and john lee matney for a rigorous panel discussion at the linda matney art gallery on saturday, may 19th at 2pm "...[stinely] and her proxies refuse to be labeled, restricted, or contained and possess an otherworldly strength beyond the surface of shiny broken fragments." -dr. margaret richardson. director@lindamatneygallery.com  #williamsburgva #newportnewsva #norfolkva #odu #artcollection  #757art #richmondva #erie  #malenude #figurativepainting #maleandfemale #3dprinting #florence  #mixedmedia #rva #artmuseum #acrylicpainting #investmentart #censored #sculpture #gilded #popsurrealism #oilpainting #femaleartist #paintings #artist #narrativeart

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
the first time i had attended a public hearing. as i had mentioned earlier during #metoo movement's #publichearing here in madras, this is a legitimate accepted form of grievance redressal system.

this hearing was on ration, pension, mgnrega and other rights and entitlements in rajasthan conducted by the mazdoor kisan shakti sangathan.

perhaps one of the most difficult photographs i had clicked during my stay in rajasthan. the state is one among those that tops the chart for silicosis. i remember shankar mama (the man holding the mic) say, "this disease is a death warrant" . corporate companies loot away the land, make mines, get labourers to work (gross human rights violations) and when they are diagnosed with silicosis, they give up on them. when the affected labourers approach the govt for remuneration for their treatment they say, 'paisa aapke family ko jaayega na. woh do saal mein hum de denge' by when, the labourers must have already lost their lives, running behind govt offices and hospitals.

to the far left corner is paras ram banjara, our saathi who was monumental in drafting and passing the mgnrega.

the stories that are entrenched in power structures that @kasturiadhikary, @shatakshi.gawade and i unearthed from the people who attended the hearing is what, that made me leave everything and say, activism is what i want to do. #mkss #mazdoorkisanshaktisangathan #publichearing #silicosis
name: Aabha M

text:
""what are you so angry about?" my mother had asked me the last time i had gone home to visit.

why aren't you more angry, i had wanted to ask her. but i couldn't talk to my mother that way. she understood that i did not want to live her life, to work as a waitress, until my toes curled in and my feet hurt all the time, to marry a man who would beat my children and treat me as if i had no right to object to object to anything he chose to do. she didn't want that life for me either. she wanted me happy and successful, to live unafraid among people who loved me, and to do things she had never been able to do and tell her all about them.

so i told her, about the shelter, the magazine, readings and discussion groups. i told her about trying to write stories, though i hesitated to send send her all that i wrote. and there were far too many times when i would sit down to write my mama and stare at the paper unable to puzzle out how to explain how urgent and unimportant it was to change how women's lives were shaped. not only that we should be paid equal money for equally difficult work, but that we should genuinely begin to think about what word we might choose to undertake, how we might live our daily lives. why should i have to marry at all? or explain myself if i chose to love a woman? why could i not spend my hours writing stories instead of raising children or keeping house or working some deadly boring job just to cover the rent of an apartments where i was not safe anyway."-dorothy allison 🌸✊️🗣sexism is a social disease #yoursistersspace

text: censorship is all around us, from social media to television to academia to government institutions. what is hidden and blocked from view reveals the cultural norms that override expression and - subsequently - artists' efforts to contest such norms. alison stinely's art was censored before finding a place at the linda matney art gallery. women artists, like stinely, have had their ideas blocked by institutions for centuries. how does her experience with censorship fit within the era of the #metoo movement? what does the silencing of female expression in today's culture mean for women? join alison stinely, diana blanchard gross, vittorio colaizzi, lita tirak and john lee matney for a rigorous panel discussion at the linda matney art gallery on saturday, may 19th at 2pm "...[stinely] and her proxies refuse to be labeled, restricted, or contained and possess an otherworldly strength beyond the surface of shiny broken fragments." -dr. margaret richardson. director@lindamatneygallery.com  #williamsburgva #newportnewsva #norfolkva #odu #artcollection  #757art #richmondva #erie  #malenude #figurativepainting #maleandfemale #3dprinting #florence  #mixedmedia #rva #artmuseum #acrylicpainting #investmentart #censored #sculpture #gilded #popsurrealism #oilpainting #femaleartist #paintings #artist #narrativeart #future
